<TEXT>
kidnappers holding two americans 
threatened the hostages safety thursday in venting their anger 
over proposals to send un troops to police lebanons stalled 
presidential elections 
a christian militia leader on thursday called for un troops in 
beirut a day after france suggested the idea 
the kidnappers warning came in a typewritten statement in 
arabic from the revolutionary justice organization the statement 
was delivered to the beirut independent newspaper annahar along 
with a polaroid picture of us hostage joseph james cicippio 
we shall use all the cards to thwart these conspiracies 
including the card of the safety of the hostages which we shall 
make the backbone of our confrontation the statement said 
the photograph showed cicippio 58 of valley forge pa in a 
navy blue track suit with red stripes sitting on a blanketcovered 
bed his hands were clasped in his lap and he was smiling as he 
faced the camera but he looked considerably thinner than in 
previous pictures released by his captors 
cicippio was acting comptroller at the american university of 
beirut when he was kidnapped on the schools campus on sept 12 
1986 
revolutionary justice believed linked to iran also claims to 
hold edward austin tracy 57 of burlington vt an author who 
was kidnapped oct 21 1986 in moslem west beirut 
the note came three days after another group islamic jihad for 
the liberation of palestine freed mithileshwar singh after 20 
months of captivity singh an indian professor is a legal 
resident of the united states 
singh was kidnapped in beirut with three american colleagues 
who are still captives a us state department team is debriefing 
singh in wiesbaden west germany and an official close to the team 
said singh was providing a lot of raw information that could be 
helpful in learning about americans still held in lebanon 
the official spoke on condition of anonymity 
the americans held with singh are jesse turner 41 a native of 
boise idaho alann steen 49 of boston and robert polhill 54 
of new york city 
sixteen foreigners including nine americans are missing in 
lebanon and believed held hostage the longest held is terry 
anderson chief middle east correspondent for the associated press 
who was kidnapped march 16 1985 
thursdays statement from cicippios kidnappers denounced the 
rude call for imperialist intervention under the slogan of 
internationalization by a colonial power whose black history is 
mothering our present tragedies 
this appeared to be a reference to france which proposed this 
week dispatching a un peacekeeping force to beirut to oversee 
election of a new president in lebanon a former french colony 
two rival moslem and christian governments emerged in lebanon 
after parliament failed to elect a new head of state to succeed 
president amin gemayel when his sixyear term expired sept 22 
the communique accused rightwing christian militants of 
collaborating with israel iraq and the north atlantic treaty 
organization to partition lebanon as a first step to turning it 
into an israeli satellite and a nato base for intrigues against 
the people of the region 
it called the christian militants the grandsons of the 
crusaders and warned we shall mete out the just punishment to 
the conspirators 
it was the first communique from revolutionary justice since 
july 7 when the group threatened to punish hostages for the 
us downing of an iranian jetliner over the persian gulf 
moslems who make up 55 percent of lebanons 4 million people 
have been fighting for an equal share of power in the nations 
13yearold civil war 
christian militia commander samir geagea on thursday echoed 
frances call for un peacekeepers in beiruts christian and 
moslem sectors to oversee presidential elections 
i propose the formation of a un force to deploy in the 
greater beirut to oversee the presidential election geagea said 
in an interview with the associated press 
geagea said the plan should include withdrawal of his lebanese 
forces militia from christian east beirut and of syrian troops and 
allied leftist and moslem militiamen from the citys western sector 
asked whether the proposed un force should remain after 
parliament elects a new president geagea said it is for the new 
president and the new cabinet he forms to decide that 
</TEXT>
