<TEXT>
a new agriculture department analysis of this 
summers droughtinduced rise in wheat prices says consumers might 
feel some effect at grocery stores at least through 1989 
past movements suggest that the droughts influence on farm 
prices of wheat will be felt for about a year at the industrial 
wholesale level and for a year and a half or more by consumers 
the report said 
the study was done by ronald a babula of the departments 
economic research service and david a bessler texas aampm 
university and reported in the current issue of agricultural 
outlook magazine 
babula said wednesday in a telephone interview that he and 
bessler are not forcasting how food prices will behave in the 
coming months prices of various items could decline but still 
leave some impact from the 1988 drought 
were not predicting anything babula said were showing 
how things have moved in the past and some of the things that 
we might expect to see happen in the future 
a statistical computer model was used to show how prices of 
wheat at the farm wholesale prices and retail prices have moved 
together in the past 
the model was then shocked with an increase in the farm 
price of wheat to simulate the 77 percent average monthly boost 
during may june and july when the effects of the drought were 
first reflected in the market 
when the farm price shock occurs processor wholesale prices 
for wheat rise immediately peaking a month after the rise in the 
farm price the report said at their highest processor prices 
increase less than half of the 77 percent increase in the farm 
price processor price increases are felt for about a year but the 
impulse generally declines in strength through time 
on the other hand the 77 percent average increase in the farm 
price of wheat generates gradual not immediate increases in 
consumer prices of wheatrelated goods the report said 
delivery sale and consumption of flour bread cake mixes 
pasta and other wheatrelated foods occur throughout the year and 
are not as closely tied to the wheat crop cycle as processing 
which includes the flour milling and baking industries 
so the consumer price effects last more than a year the 
report said consumer price rises peak at seven months but 
prices stay relatively high until 17 to 20 months after the 
initiating farm price shock the increase in consumer prices is 
smaller but more enduring than the jump in processor prices 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
some promising new biological weapons are 
being used in the war against marauding grasshoppers says the 
agriculture department 
in one development two commercial firms evans biocontrol inc 
of broomfield colo and bozeman bio tech of bozeman mont have 
adapted usda technology for producing and storing a parasite 
nosema lucustae department studies show the parasite kills 50 
percent to 60 percent of grasshoppers in three to four weeks 
the basic tests and development were done by the departments 
agricultural research service at the agencys rangeland insect 
laboratory in bozeman by je henry and colleagues 
henry said the parasite is available to homeowners and ranchers 
through regional agents and on contract to government agencies 
which use it on a large scale in the west grasshoppers cause an 
estimated 400 million in damage to grass and crops each year he 
said 
spores of the parasite are put on wheat bran flakes to form a 
bait after the insects eat the bait the organism attacks the 
pests fat cells and depletes its energy stores henry said in a 
report issued here on wednesday 
the parasite remains in the grasshopper population because sick 
females pass it on to offspring and survivors eat dead relatives 
he said 
meanwhile another development involves an agreement with evans 
biotechnical to field test another natural killer grasshopper 
entomopoxvirus the agency said in laboratory tests the virus 
kills 20 percent to 30 percent of the grasshoppers right away and 
stunts the growth of an additional 20 percent to 30 percent 
doug a streett an entomoligist at the agencys bozeman 
laboratory said evans biocontrol plans to produce the virus and 
mix it with the parasite for tests on 1000 acres in the west 
streett said that in combination the two ingredients may work 
more rapidly to kill the grasshoppers 
