<TEXT>
a new house bill designed to combat the 
greenhouse effect or global warming trend would require a 
wide range of energysaving measures including a higher gas 
guzzler tax and rebates for buyers of fuelefficient autos 
republican and democratic lawmakers said wednesday in 
introducing the legislation that they did not expect action on the 
bill before congress adjourns next week 
the reagan administration has said more study is needed before 
taking action to curb the greenhouse effect 
rep claudine schneider rri chief architect of the new 
proposal said available options for reducing greenhouse gases such 
as carbon dioxide can vary in cost by tenfold or more 
this makes it imperative that the strategy the federal 
government undertakes in formulating global warming prevention 
policies avoids imposing needless and wasteful expenditures 
she said 
the global warming trend which some scientists say already has 
begun could raise the average temperature of the earth by 3 
degrees to 8 degrees in the middle of the next century 
the warming comes about because gases arising from human 
activity build up in the atmosphere trapping radiant heat that 
normally would escape to space the most important gas carbon 
dioxide comes from the burning of fossil fuels such as oil and 
coal 
also on wednesday a report from the environmental and energy 
study institute a companion organization to the congressional 
environmental and energy study conference called for a first 
priority on energy efficiency by the next administration 
the report said political leaders must be willing to raise the 
consumer cost of using fuels that produce carbon dioxide a 
prominent example would be gasoline 
ms schneiders measure calls for substantial increases in funds 
for research and development modification of federal buildings to 
create 40 percent energy savings by the end of the century tough 
efficiency standards for electric lights and major increases in 
auto fuel efficiency along with a higher gasguzzler tax and 
rebates for buyers of efficient models 
