<TEXT>
the government says it will ban public 
drinking in eight english cities next year in an experimental 
crackdown on socalled lager louts rowdy youths who get drunk 
on americanstyle beer 
home secretary douglas hurd said the bans would take effect 
early next year in coventry bath farnborough chester st 
austell scarborough aldershot and newquay 
the government does not want to restrict personal freedom 
hurd told a legal conference wednesday but it is not clever 
masculine or attractive to drink yourself into a state where you 
break windows or hit or stab a policemen 
the twoyear experimental program calls for local governments to 
work with the home office to enact bylaws empowering the courts to 
levy 170 fines against people who drink alcohol outdoors 
the measure follows a wave of summer violence in britains 
suburbs and rural towns by young men most of them between the ages 
of 18 and 26 who gather on weekends and drink on the streets or in 
local pubs 
they have been blamed for brawls vandalism and attacks on 
unarmed police called to disperse the drunken rowdy crowds 
police estimate dozens of officers have been injured in 
confrontations nationwide with the socalled lager louts lager 
is a pale americanstyle beer favored by the young as opposed to 
the dark traditional bitter english beer 
traditionally britons have been allowed to consume alcohol in 
parks or on the streets particularly during the afternoon when 
pubs are closed 
but the 73yearold pubclosing law was repealed aug 22 giving 
people who want a pint of beer in the afternoon the option to drink 
indoors 
hurd said wednesday he had misgivings about making drinking on 
the streets a criminal offense 
but i concluded that the distress caused to ordinary 
citizens by groups of mainly young people becoming drunk and 
behaving badly was such that it was worth trying a bylaw he 
said 
in a meeting today with the chief police officers association in 
the northern city of preston hurd was to be asked to endorse 
another experimental program installing video cameras in downtown 
areas to keep on eye on drunken youths 
</TEXT>
