<TEXT>
after lurching through bloodshed and 
political upheaval burma is almost back to where it was 11 weeks 
ago with an authoritarian government and few prospects for the 
democracy that once seemed so close 
since the resignation of strongman ne win on july 23 several 
thousand people have died hundreds of thousands marched in the 
streets in a nationwide uprising and three leaders took turns at 
the helm 
now some western experts say the best hope for the 
prodemocracy forces is that the government will offer political 
and economic liberalization to appease an angry population 
pressure for change they say may also come from burmas vital 
foreign aid donors 
given all thats happened its silly to write the opposition 
off but overall i think the army is sitting squarely on top of the 
people for at least the next few weeks said a western diplomat 
in bangkok 
the recent chaotic events amounted to the largest 
antigovernment movement in the past 26 years of autocratic rule 
and the most intense and widespread display of people power 
since the burmese fight for independence from great britain 
but the ruling oligarchy of military men around ne win despite 
earlier rumors that they were about to flee the country dug in 
maneuvered with what some analysts say was machiavellian 
brilliance and at the very least temporarily won the day 
as the drama unfolded burma experts offered a number of 
possible scenarios including one that called for the military to 
shoot as many protestors as necessary to retain power 
this is the option it chose together with what one western 
ambassador in rangoon described as a devilish plot of stoking 
chaos and anxiety among masses who grew increasingly short of food 
fuel and other necessities 
the people have been beaten over the head for two months they 
never got weapons and they were never really organized and the 
army never cracked said american burma scholar josef silverstein 
although the government has promised general elections a key 
opposition leader former defense minister tin oo told the 
associated press all the opposition leaders are now facing 
arrest and other punitive measures so what can i say the 
situation is so undemocratic 
opponents appear to have little maneuvering room their major 
weapon a general strike that began aug 8 was blunted when civil 
servants and factory workers threatened by dismissal returned to 
their jobs oct 3 
rather than a single united opposition at least four 
antigovernment parties have emerged while the more radical 
students who spearheaded the demonstrations are fleeing to the 
thaiburmese border to get guerrilla training from ethnic minority 
rebels 
by contrast the conservative party has the benefit of big 
coffers a nationwide network built up over 26 years and a body of 
loyalists who stand to lose sizable perks should the opposition 
win despite efforts to officially divorce the national unity party 
from the government analysts agree it is a major instrument of the 
militarybacked leadership 
prior to the current upheavals the party then known as the 
burma program socialist party claimed that more than 14 million 
out of burmas 38 million people were members of either the party 
or its affiliates 
silverstein and others say the leaderships weak spot is the 
shattered economy and dependence on foreign aid to mount a revival 
japan which supplies about 80 percent of foreign loans and 
grants and other donors have frozen assistance but whether tokyo 
choses to use its considerable clout to shape events inside burma 
remains uncertain 
this is a lever the military has to cope with if anything can 
now leverage the situation its going to be the need for outside 
assistance silverstein said 
