developing nations 
the question is whether that understanding will lead to 
solutions to the problem the outgoing president said in an 
interview with the associated press 
de la madrid also said that mexico will respond to the stronger 
showing by opposition parties in july 6 general elections and 
become a more democratic country 
de la madrid 54 leaves office dec 1 his institutional 
revolutionary party has governed mexico since 1929 and will 
continue to do so under presidentelect carlos salinas de gortari 
de la madrid has been a leader in demanding better debt payment 
conditions for the third world but at the same time has maintained 
mexicos commitment to pay 
mexico has renegotiated its debt and made service payments of 
more than 75 billion in the past six years that de la madrid has 
been president but the principal is 104 billion a few billion 
more than when de la madrid took office 
pointing to mexico as an example de la madrid said debtor 
nations must set our house in order internally with economic 
measures and demand at the same time a fair and realistic deal 
from creditors 
he said some world leaders and banks now realize that the debt 
affects the entire world economy 
mexico insists on joint responsibility of debtor and creditor 
for the debt he said 
he said the institutional revolutionary party must modernize 
while retaining its principles but become more efficient in 
working with the grassroots membership 
however the opposition leftist and rightist parties also must 
realize the times they live in and update their ideology change 
tactics and present articulate programs to the people he said 
he said the relative strengthening of the opposition is a 
small price to pay for the strengthening of political pluralism 
political reforms de la madrid initiated led to greater 
opposition representation in congress 
relaxed and smiling easily during the interview de la madrid 
recalled that when he took office the country had just 100 million 
in reserves citizens were disenchanted with a political system 
which though stable was fraught with corruption 
the world oil price collapse had shattered mexican dreams of 
abundance of citizens told two years earlier that they were on 
their way to prosperity 
there is general agreement that the stocky unpretentious 
president who dealt out strong economic medicine held together a 
country on the verge of social conflict six years ago 
the most serious problem at the time was the lack of 
confidence of mexicans in themselves and the conflict between 
social groups my concern was to maintain peace and individual 
freedoms while trying to obtain a social consensus he said 
de la madrid enacted measures that eliminated many subsidies 
prices went up and salaries lost more than half their buying power 
he was accused of favoring the elite 
through the pri dominance of labor unions he kept protests down 
and eventually got labor government and private business to agree 
on a wage and price control plan that reduced inflation to an 
estimated 50 percent for this year down from 1592 percent in 1987 
de la madrid brought mexico into the general agreement on trade 
and tariffs opening mexicos markets and forcing its manufacturers 
to compete 
the manufacturing industrys exports in 1972 paid for only 26 
percent of its imports in 1987 they paid for 98 percent of the 
imports 
international dollar reserves climbed to 15 billion this year 
as nonoil exports made up for the large drop in petroleum income 
i am satisfied that some progress was made de la madrid 
said but he acknowledged things will not be easy for salinas de 
gortari 
