<TEXT>
the house on thursday passed legislation 
designed to end the united states trusteeship over palau the last 
western pacific island nation still covered by the trusteeships set 
up by the united nations in 1947 
the bill sent to the senate by a 40611 vote would authorize 
the president to enter into a compact of free association with 
palau once the micronesian nation of 14000 people approves the 
plan 
us officials have told congress that palau is a strategically 
important area that could host us military and naval bases if a 
new defense basing agreement cannot be worked out with the 
philippines 
under the proposed compact the united states would gain basing 
rights in palau and would be responsible for defending the islands 
the future of the legislation was uncertain as congress worked 
toward adjournment next week 
a senate energy and natural resources committee aide speaking 
on condition of anonymity said key members of the panel are 
opposed to the plan drafted by the house interior committees 
insular and territorial affairs subcommittee 
the aide said the main problem involves about 40 million in 
assistance to palau proposed by the house in addition to the 460 
million in aid over 15 years that was contained in 1986 legislation 
approving the proposed compact 
senators are taking the position that the 1986 agreement between 
the house and senate on the compactapproval bill still stands and 
that if palau wants more money it can return later to congress 
according to the aide 
house committee leaders including chairman morris udall 
dariz and ron de lugo the delegate from the virgin islands 
have quoted palau officials as saying the extra 40 million is 
needed to ensure compact approval by palau voters 
palauans have held six plebiscites since 1982 but each has 
fallen short of approving the free association arrangement that is 
similar to ones the united states has with two other former trust 
territories the marshall islands and the federated states of 
micronesia 
the problem in palau is that nations constitutional prohibition 
against nuclear weapons on its territory each plebiscite has won a 
majority but came up short of the 75 percent support needed to 
overrule the nonukes provision 
the compact process has seen the killing of one palau president 
the recent suicide of another deep political divisions reports of 
intimidation and harassment of compact opponents and allegations of 
governmental corruption 
the extra money proposed by udall and de lugo would pay for 
antidrug programs and special auditors to monitor the palau 
government their bill also would authorize palau to use 28 
million in compact funds to help pay off a controversial power 
plant that figured prominently in corruption allegations 
