<TEXT>
a virus is causing an epidemic of 
genital warts and appears to underlie the rise in cervical cancer 
a doctor said at a science writers meeting 
it is now clear that transmission of these viral agents has 
reached epidemic proportions dr gary schoolnik an associate 
professor at the stanford university medical center said wednesday 
at the meeting held by the american medical association 
the infection known as papilloma virus is a group of 46 
viruses that cause warts of the dozen or more of the viruses that 
cause genital warts five have been firmly linked to precancerous 
changes in cervical cells the cervix is the opening of the uterus 
the five viruses are often missed by traditional pap smear 
examinations 
but the food and drug administration is expected to approve a 
test within weeks that detects the virus with far greater accuracy 
and can determine when a very dangerous form of the virus is 
present schoolnik said 
genital papilloma virus infections are the most common sexually 
transmitted disease in many communities more frequent than 
syphilis gonorrhea chlamydia and herpes he said 
schoolnik called the infection the sexually transmitted 
disease of the 90s following herpes in the 70s and deadly aids 
in the 80s 
the rate of genital warts has increased six fold in the past 10 
years he said 
a survey of san francisco bay area adolescent clinics found that 
20 percent of sexually active girls between 14 and 18 years old 
were infected by the virus said schoolnik who conducted the 
survey 
last year 14000 american women were diagnosed with cervical 
cancer which can be cured if detected early but is fatal if left 
untreated 
</TEXT>
