<TEXT>
president kennedy worried that leaks from congress 
about his military chiefs testimony would scuttle the historic 
nuclear test ban treaty according to secret oval office tapes 
released thursday 
the conversations involving kennedy his top advisers and senate 
leaders in the summer of 1963 show a president personally engaged 
in the strategy nosecounting and public relations required to 
push a major treaty through the us senate 
kennedys chief worry was that a hostile senate subcommittee 
would get the military brass to testify first in private then 
selectively leak portions of the testimony to suggest that the 
military leaders had doubts 
in the end however kennedy steered the limited nuclear treaty 
to an 8019 vote and signed it in his office on oct 7 1963 
exactly 25 years ago friday the anniversary prompted the kennedy 
library to make public the material on the treaty which was a 
portion of tapes whose existence was disclosed in 1973 
on aug 12 1963 kennedy spoke with a senate ally democrat 
mike mansfield of montana and shared his anxiety over the 
positions of sens henry scoop jackson of washington barry 
goldwater of arizona and strom thurmond of south carolina 
in my opinion the chiefs joint chiefs of staff are the key 
and what they will say in public would be more protreaty than what 
they will say under interrogation by scoop jackson with leading 
questions and barry goldwater and strom kennedy told mansfield 
the president wanted the chiefs to testfy first in public 
before the foreign relations committee chaired by the more 
sympathetic william fulbright of arkansas kennedy wanted to head 
off closed testimony by the chiefs before the armed services 
subcommittee on preparedness investigation chaired by conservative 
democrat john stennis of mississippi 
what i am concerned about is that these chiefs will write in 
private a record which they will then feel obliged to sustain in 
public well if we could get them on public record and publicize 
that to the nation then whatever was leaked out of the committee 
would have much less impact 
mansfield remained worried warning against getting stennis 
back up 
yeah well this is bigger than than stennis kennedy said 
the limited nuclear test ban treaty was initialed in moscow on 
aug 5 1963 between the soviet union the united states and great 
britain the three nations agreed to ban nuclear explosions in the 
air underwater and on land but allowed continued testing 
underground 
kennedy had proposed a comprehensive ban but soviet leader 
nikita s khrushchev vetoed the idea said sheldon stern a 
historian at the kennedy library since 1963 the issue of a total 
ban has arisen several times but the superpowers have never agreed 
stern said the oval office tapes included no dramatic 
revelations but supplied a closeup look at the treaty process 
its a mixture of so many different levels of concern 
constitutional diplomatic political personal stern said 
the tapes reveal that kennedy was well aware of the sales job he 
faced to win a twothirds ratification vote in the senate and he 
made sure to enlist former presidents truman and eisenhower 
in july kennedy spoke with secretary of state dean rusk and 
proposed giving a presidential speech in favor of the treaty 
we got to hit the country while the countrys hot thats the 
only thing that makes any impression to these goddamned senators 
said kennedy who had left the senate himself just 2 years earlier 
