<TEXT>
air traffic controllers in washington will manage 
the flow of planes into ohare international airport a move to 
help local controllers and clear congested skies the 
transportation department announced thursday 
transportation secretary jim burnley announced the change one 
day after the federal aviation administration reduced the number of 
departures and arrivals at ohare 
this year controllers at ohare have made 30 errors more than 
twice the mistakes recorded in 1987 four were made since last 
friday 
under the plan announced late thursday controllers at the faas 
central flow control headquarters in washington will monitor air 
traffic at ohare to enforce the limit of 155 departures and 
landings during daily peak hours 
it may be that they delay an airplane taking off at another 
facility it may be that they slow an airplane down said 
transportation deputy secretary mimi dawson 
i dont see it as a reprimand she said chicago is an 
anomaly we feel this is an appropriate action 
chicago controllers ms dawson said will still be responsible 
for directing planes to runways once they enter ohares air space 
were not managing the traffic in chicago she added 
were not managing approaches and departures from washington 
we just want to make sure that the amount of traffic stays within 
the limits 
during peak periods between 445 pm and 915 pm the 
maximum number of planes allowed to depart and land in good weather 
now has been reduced to 155 per hour from 180 at ohare 
the plan also affects some planes at midway airport on the 
southwest side because the airports share air space 
burnley said his department will study whether those limits are 
effective 
i have ordered these actions because todays operating 
environment in the chicago area may require new traffic management 
procedures in order to assure continued safety burnley said 
controllers at ohare the nations busiest airport made two 
errors friday one sunday and one tuesday the faa said ohare 
controllers 30 errors this year compared to 12 in 1987 the faa 
has said 
in comparison atlantas hartsfield international airport the 
nations second busiest has had just six errors this year and 
washingtons national airport just two officials said 
the latest incident at ohare came just two months after the 
national transportation safety board issued a report saying that 
chronic understaffing of controllers mandatory overtime outdated 
equipment and inadequate training contributed to mistakes at ohare 
