the congressional black caucus plans to issue 
a code of conduct for japanese businesses expecting sell their 
products to black americans the caucus chairman said thursday 
rep mervyn dymally dcalif announced at a caucus hearing 
that the code to be issued in a few weeks will aim to correct 
what he called japanese economic arrogance and insensitivity 
toward black america 
he said the code would be along the lines of the former sullivan 
principles a code of conduct intended to help the black majority 
in whiteruled south africa through training and enlightened labor 
standards to which us companies operating in south africa were 
asked to adhere 
the code was named for the rev leon sullivan a philadelphia 
civil rights leader who later announced he has decided to press for 
total disengagement of us corporations from south africa 
the forthcoming code would be aimed at japanese corporations and 
their us subsidiaries said dymally 
it would seek an end to racial stereotypes and caricatures 
offensive to blacks such as the black sambo dolls exported by 
japan and the hiring of more blacks as executives in us 
factories and distributorships of japanese concerns 
the efforts at persuasion would be backed by a buy america 
campaign during the christmas shopping season to demonstrate the 
purchasing power of us blacks who in the 1980 census numbered 
more than 26 million he said 
the black caucus approach was described as too weak by some 
speakers at the hearing and unrealistic by others 
