<TEXT>
attorneys for the soviet union and the us 
government joined forces in federal appeals court thursday arguing 
that international relations will suffer if an american 
businessmans lawsuit is upheld 
we have been working very closely with the soviets and we have 
made wonderful progress said justice department attorney douglas 
letter its important that this progress not be set back 
he was addressing a threejudge panel of the 9th us circuit 
court of appeals which is considering the case of raphael 
gregorian an american denounced by the soviets and barred from 
doing business in moscow after 14 years 
one of the judges stephen reinhard bristled at the mention of 
foreign relations saying isnt that something were supposed to 
ignore the political considerations in reaching our decision 
gregorian has sued the soviets for libel the soviets have 
resisted and the us state department has sided with the soviets 
saying they may not be sued for libel in the united states 
gregorians attorney gerald kroll ridiculed the contention 
that the case endangers ussoviet relations 
i personally think they have bigger people to fry than my 
client kroll told the court ive never heard that we couldnt 
conclude an arms agreement because of raphael gregorian 
john mage a new york attorney representing the soviets 
insisted that us courts do not have jurisdiction because 
incidents involving gregorian did not occur in the united states 
he also said the nation is immune from suit as a foreign sovereign 
its really two against one kroll said of the us and 
soviet alignment in court he has expressed bitterness over the 
governments abandonment of one of its own citizens in the legal 
proceedings 
i look at this as a contest of politics versus justice said 
kroll theres never been a case exactly like this before 
gregorians problems began in 1984 when after a 14year 
amicable relationship the soviets suddenly revoked gregorians 
permit to sell medical supplies in the soviet union until then 
his california international trade corp based in palo alto 
calif had done a thriving business exporting such items as kidney 
dialysis machines heartlung machines and batteries for heart 
pacemakers 
soon after revoking his permit the soviets through the 
official newspaper izvestia printed a story denouncing gregorian 
as a duplicitous negotiatior accusing him of bribery and 
smuggling and intimating he was a us spy 
gregorian adamant about his innocence took an unprecedented 
action suing the soviet union for libel in us courts he also 
demanded that the soviets pay for medical equipment still in moscow 
the soviet defendants at first ignored the suit but in 1985 
us district judge david kenyon entered a default judgment against 
them in los angeles awarding gregorian total damages of 413000 
of that amount 250000 was for libel 
the soviets refused to pay kroll said he would seize soviet 
assets and to dramatize his claim he took custody of a typewriter 
at an izvestia correspondents washington dc home as partial 
payment 
then soviet and us state department lawyers went to court 
the soviet agency vo medexport which did business with 
gregorian asserted its immunity from suit under the foreign 
sovereign immunities act and moved to reverse the judgment 
on april 5 1987 kenyon dismissed his own libel judgment 
ruling that he did not have jurisdiction because of immunity 
considerations however he let stand his ruling the soviets should 
meet their contractual obligation to pay for the medical supplies 
kroll appealed the ruling on libel to the 9th circuit the 
soviets appealed the contractual award as well as disputing the 
libel claim 
krolls argument is based on a theory that libel in connection 
with a commercial activity is exempt from immunities act and must 
be tried as a civil claim in us courts 
new york attorney martin popper who represents the soviets 
said in his legal brief that there is no precedent for such a claim 
plaintiffs fail to cite a decision of any court in the entire 
world including the united states that has asserted jurisdiction 
on a claim of libel against a foreign sovereign popper said 
the justice departments brief sided with the soviets saying 
congress did not intend that foreign states could be sued for 
claims of libel 
an additional view on the case has come from the washington 
legal foundation a public interest law and policy center which 
filed a friend of the court brief for gregorian 
wlf believes that the outrageous nature of the lies published 
by defendantsappellants is such that they should be held 
accountable the foundations lawyers argued a ruling for the 
soviets they said would reduce the ability of us courts to 
protect the rights of citizens doing business overseas 
