<TEXT>
opposition leaders said thursday a new 
emergency law gives president daniel ortega dictatorial powers and 
is likely to be applied soon 
the law approved wednesday by the national assembly gives the 
president authority to declare a state of emergency and restrict 
civil rights for reasons of war economic crisis or national 
disaster it took effect immediately 
usbacked rebels known as contras have been fighting to 
overthrow the leftist government since 1981 and nicaragua is in an 
economic crisis 
the opposition in the 96seat assembly said in a statement that 
the law bestows on ortega too great a concentration of 
extraordinary powers making him an absolute dictator 
erick ramirez president of the social christian party said 
the new law consolidates the dictatorial and totalitarian state 
and just as in the chile of president gen augusto pinochet the 
nicaraguan people should say no to the sandinistas 
chileans voted wednesday against letting pinochet extend his 
15year rule 
ramirez complained that the law legalizes repression against 
the internal opposition to consolidate the power of the sandinistas 
and gives the us congress arguments for pushing military aid for 
the contras 
both ramirez and enrique gurdian acting president of the 
nicaraguan democratic coordinate the countrys main opposition 
group said the government could be expected to apply the law soon 
an emergency decree was in effect in nicaragua most of the time 
from march 1982 until shortly after a regional peace plan was 
signed by the five central american presidents in august 1987 
the decrees provisions included press censorship suspension of 
some civil rights and searches without warrants 
the new law goes further it allows the president to close news 
media and theaters intervene in mail or electronic correspondence 
take over private vehicles and businesses make preventive arrests 
and prevent individuals from entering or leaving the country 
it gives the president authority to expand or reduce his own 
authority to take the steps and to continue the measures until the 
reasons for them disappear 
the law says certain basic rights cannot be suspended they 
include the rights to life equality freedom of conscience 
asylum thought and religion to be presumed innocent until proven 
guilty to have personal property and to be free from slavery in 
prison 
the national assembly on thursday also approved legislation 
banning the receipt of any type of assistance approved by the us 
congress and destined for opposition groups the roman catholic 
church labor unions and individuals 
under the law any person found to have accepted us assistance 
could face between four and 12 years imprisonment 
president reagan signed a new 27 million sixmonth 
nonmilitary aid package for the contras oct 1 
on tuesday honduras asked the united nations to set up an 
international peace force to take contras and leftist salvadoran 
rebels from its territory it said the rebels should be taken first 
to costa rica and guatemala then resettled elsewhere 
thursday in san jose the capital of costa rica assistant 
foreign minister carlos rivera rejected that proposal 
rivera told reporters relocating the contras in costa rica would 
violate that countrys principles of neutrality the only way the 
proposal could be considered would be for the rebels to abandon the 
war and become refugees or political exiles rivera said 
a rebel leader said thursday that some contras in honduras were 
returning to nicaragua enrique bermudez said in a telephone 
interview from miami that our troops are returning to their 
original positions inside nicaragua 
the report could not be immediately confirmed a rebel spokesman 
in tegucigalpa the honduran capital acknowledged some contra 
forces had returned to nicaraguan border provinces but declined to 
provide details the official spoke on condition of anonymity 
contras have used base camps on the honduran side of the border 
since they began fighting in 1981 to overthrow the sandinista 
government 
