<TEXT>
a texas company and two of its executives were 
accused thursday of participating with a postal service governor in 
a contract bidrigging scheme that included replacing the 
postmaster general 
the replacement of paul n carlin with albert v casey as 
postmaster general was engineered in 1986 as part of the elaborate 
effort by recognition equipment inc to get 400 million worth of 
contracts to provide automated mailsorting equipment according an 
indictment returned here 
the indictment charged that the company reis chairman william 
g moore jr and robert w reedy a vice president conspired with 
peter e voss then vice chairman of the postal service board of 
governors and others to manipulate bid procedures obtain 
confidential information about competitors and replace carlin 
considered an obstacle to rei winning contracts 
an unindicted coconspirator voss received 19000 in kickbacks 
plus 4000 worth of airline tickets from a detroitarea public 
relations firm headed by john r gnau jr that rei hired on voss 
recommendation the indictment said 
voss who received a fouryear sentence for his 1986 guilty plea 
in the case also was promised onequarter of one percent of any 
revenues rei earned from postal service contracts it said 
the indictment charged that through voss rei arranged for the 
postal service in 1985 to halt procurement of a multiline optical 
character reader system and set up a twostep test period to give 
it another chance to win the lucrative order 
after the procurement scheme came to light in 1986 the postal 
service ultimately decided to give the revised contract to 
electrocom automation inc which had beat out rei for the earlier 
phase of the contract 
but if rei had won the competition it would have been 
positioned to obtain procurement contracts worth 46 billion over 
the next five years said postal service spokesman james van loozen 
voss who headed president reagans 1980 ohio presidential 
campaign pleaded guilty to charges he took kickbacks totaling at 
least 30000 on four postal service contracts and expense account 
fraud 
gnau another unindicted coconspirator who headed reagans 1980 
michigan campaign received a threeyear sentence for conspiracy 
and for paying an illegal 2500 gratuity to voss 
gnau agreed to cooperate with the investigation along with 
another executive of his firm michael b marcus who received a 
sixmonth sentence for paying illegal gratuities to voss 
van loozen said the bid rigging scandal delayed procurement of a 
new optical mailscanner system for about 14 months the system is 
now expected to be completely installed next may 
in sentencing memos filed in the earlier cases prosecutors 
estimated that the bidrigging activities of voss and gnau cost the 
postal service hundreds of millions of dollars the agency planned 
to save through automation 
the indictment charged rei moore 49 and reedy 46 both of 
dallas with conspiracy to defraud the government theft of postal 
service property mail and wire fraud and aiding and abetting 
moore and reedy each face maximum possible prison terms of 33 
years and fines of more than 15 million if convicted the company 
could be fined more than 3 million if convicted 
rei spokeswoman jenny barker said neither the company nor mr 
moore nor mr reedy have done anything wrong we do not believe the 
indictment should have been brought by the us attorney 
the company mr moore and mr reedy intend to defend this 
matter to the fullest extent we are confident we will be 
exonerated she said 
in a statement us attorney jay b stevens said public 
corruption is one of democracys worst enemies this indictment 
represents our commitment to prosecute aggressively and vigorously 
those who seek to strike at the heart of fairness in the 
procurement process by corrupting the machinery of government for 
personal financial gain 
according to the indictment william a spartin president of 
gnau amp associates who also headed an executive placement firm 
influenced the selection of a new postmaster by obtaining 
management consulting contracts with the postal service 
spartin also named an unindicted coconspirator used his 
position to insinuate himself into the confidence of highlevel 
usps and board officials but concealed his relationship to voss 
gnau and rei 
casey who became postmaster general in january 1986 and served 
only seven months until early august 1986 was one of three 
candidates that spartin recommended through voss as a replacement 
for carlin 
spartin who concealed from casey his interest in reis effort 
to get a mailsorting contract also was instrumental in the 
removal of james v jellison a deputy postmaster general who was 
also regarded as an obstacle the indictment charged 
spartin is also cooperating with authorities in the 
investigation according to sources who spoke on condition of 
anonymity 
the procurement scheme began to unravel when some postal 
inspectors aboard a commercial airline noticed voss traveling in 
coach even though postal governors were allowed to fly first 
class sources said 
tracing his expense account vouchers inspectors discovered that 
voss had collected reimbursement for 70000 worth of firstclass 
air travel when he spent only 26000 on coach seats a prosecutor 
said when voss pleaded guilty to embezzlement 
casey was succeeded as postmaster general in august 1986 by new 
york businessman preston r tisch he held the job until anthony m 
frank a san francisco banker took over last march 1 
</TEXT>
