<TEXT>
the president sukarno who died in 
disgrace 18 years ago is again stirring controversy in the nation 
he led to independence from the dutch after world war ii 
two recently published books spotlight the leader whose vivid 
personality has an almost mythic hold on many indonesians who refer 
to themselves as sukarnoists 
in the memoirs of col bambang widjanarko his military aide 
from 1960 to 1968 sukarno is portrayed as helplessly buffeted by 
political forces beyond his control during an aborted communist 
coup sept 30 1965 
some critics complained that bambangs eight years near 
sukarno glosses over sukarnos shortcomings but it is the less 
controversial of the two books 
the other book in the view of sukarnoists should be banned for 
blackening the reputation of the nations cofounder 
it is titled he who sows the wind will reap the storm and 
says sukarno was involved in the aborted coup and was a committed 
marxist since his student days in the 1920s 
written by sugiarso surojo a former intelligence officer who 
now edits a womens magazine he who sows describes sukarno as 
a conspirator adept at concealing his true identity 
charges of complicity in the uprising in which six top army 
generals were slain are not new several military tribunals heard 
testimony years ago that sukarno knew the coup was planned but did 
nothing to prevent it 
earlier foes also denounced what they saw as his demogoguery 
hedonistic lifestyle and tilt toward the communist party which is 
now banned 
sukarno remained as president in name only after signing over 
power on march 11 1966 to maj gen suharto who foiled the 
revolt five months earlier sukarno and suharto who is now 66 are 
the only presidents this country has known 
sugiarso said he was inspired to write his book partly by the 
revival of sukarnoism during last years general election campaign 
thousands of young indonesians in red tshirts and headbands 
thronged rallies in support of the indonesian democratic party a 
grouping of five political parties one of which was founded by 
sukarno 61 years ago the party had been faring poorly and its 
leaders calculated correctly that the sukarno magnetism would help 
revive its fortunes 
with megawati sukarno one of sukarnos daughters among the 
successful candidates last year the party increased its 
representation in the 500seat parliament from 24 to 40 members and 
its proportion of the total vote from 79 to 11 percent 
with sukarnoism making a comeback among youth sugiarso said 
his book is intended to balance what he called a lopsided view of 
history fostered by the countrys founding generation 
the time has come for our national history to be straightened 
written objectively so as to be a mirror for our future leaders 
and for the young generation who have not known their true national 
history he said 
attorney general sukarton marmosudjono described the book as 
unethical but rejected calls to ban it home affairs minister 
rudini also objected to the book and lt gen harsudiono hartas 
chief of the armed forces social and political section urged a 
stop to the sukarno polemic 
no sales figures were available but booksellers said it was 
moving briskly 
sukarno was officially forgotten and rarely mentioned favorably 
in ruling circles after his death at the age of 69 from a kidney 
ailment june 21 1970 
once hailed for his vision of a unified nation free of dutch 
colonial rule his economic policies had virtually bankrupted 
indonesia 
popular interest in sukarno was reignited after the government 
decided in 1979 to build an elaborate tomb for his remains 
replacing a simple grave that was covered by a faded yellow parasol 
newspapers were allowed for the first time in years to mention 
his name portraits of sukarno went on sale and a twoweek exhibit 
of memorabilia attracted throngs books he wrote books came off the 
banned list 
statues of sukarno and the countrys first vice president and 
cofounder mohammad hatta were dedicated in 1980 at the site 
where they declared independence on aug 17 1945 hatta resigned 
in 1956 partly as a result of disenchantment with sukarnos 
leadership and died in 1980 
jakartas efficient new airport was renamed the sukarnohatta 
international airport three years ago 
the son of a schoolteacher and a balinese dancer sukarno became 
one of the best known nationalists in what then was the netherlands 
east indies after forming a political party in 1927 the dutch 
sentenced him to four years in prison in 1929 
freed in 1931 he was arrested again the following year and 
spent the next eight years in exile in the outer islands his exile 
ended when the japanese invaded during world war ii and freed him 
some indonesians accused him of collaborating with the japanese 
following their declaration of independence in 1945 sukarno and 
hatta raised an army and and took to the jungle for a fouryear 
struggle against the dutch 
although the dutch captured and again exiled sukarno in 1948 
his battle for independence stirred world opinion and the united 
nations urged freedom for the nation sukarno was freed in 1949 and 
later that year the dutch relinquished power 
</TEXT>
