<TEXT>
some people are betting that the devastating 
drought of 1988 is over that next year will see a return to 
normalcy in us crop production after all they say thats been 
the historical pattern 
there were helpful rains the last couple of months and the crop 
growing season has virtually ended so there is less news about the 
drought although in huge areas of the nation dryness still 
prevails the deep subsoil kind that will require a foot or two of 
precipitation to remedy 
all in all say agriculture department economists most farmers 
and ranchers have survived the crop and pasture losses better than 
some thought possible at midyear when heat and drought were so 
rampant 
one important note of optimism came recently from the 
departments economic research service drought temporarily slowed 
the recovery in farmland values but appraisers think land prices 
will climb at a healthy clip in 1989 
land prices primarily reflect longterm expectations for farm 
income interest rates and other factors says agency economist 
roger hexem but shortterm events such as the drought can reduce 
farmers liquidity which in turn reduces the demand for farmland 
or increases supply of land on the market if farms fail 
a survey of rural appraisers in august indicated that farmland 
prices nationwide rose 12 percent from may 1 to the end of july 
slightly behind the 18 percent increase for the preceding three 
months looking to this fall the appraisers said they expected 
land values to rise an average of only 09 percent from aug 1 
through october 
but they also indicated farmland values may rise 46 percent in 
1989 faster than a 36 percent increase forecast last may prior to 
the main drought impact 
if the inflation rate continues to edge upward farmland 
values may improve hexem said however wariness about next 
years growing conditions farm incomes and interest rates seem to 
be dampening the nearterm outlook particularly in areas where the 
drought has been most severe 
by reducing grain output driving up commodity prices and 
putting livestock producers in a bind for forage and emergency feed 
supplies the drought took a further toll of producers who had 
suffered the financial crunch of earlier years 
there likely wont be as many farms next year as there would 
have been without the 1988 drought says another agency 
economist clark edwards in the october issue of agricultural 
outlook magazine 
drought he said created financial hardships that have 
accelerated many of the forces that were already leading to fewer 
but larger farms in the united states 
this consolidation or decline in farm numbers occurred rapidly 
averaging almost 3 percent a year after the peak in 1935 of 
681 million farms then in the early 1970s exploding export 
markets made farming financially attractive 
according to the 1982 census of agriculture edwards said the 
number of farms in the preceding decade declined only 04 percent a 
year 
in the early 1980s as lower commodity prices and rising 
interest rates squeezed producers profits from farmland dropped 
and so did land values farm numbers declined again and 
consolidations increased 
farmers hurt most by the drought are offering land for sale or 
rent in sufficient numbers to slow the rise in land values that 
began last year following six years of decline edwards said 
this lowers the price of land relative to its value leading to 
further consolidations by farmers with growth potential 
but the drought is causing consolidation differently according 
to region in winter wheat areas of the southern great plains 
yields were high this year and with rising market prices the 
consolidation would be somewhat like that experienced in boom 
times including a slowing in the rate of exit from farming he 
said 
but for farmers growing spring wheat in the northern plains 
production was down by half incomes were cut and the 
consolidation would be more like that experienced during bust 
times edwards said 
urbanization conversion to nonfarm uses rising transportation 
costs and expenses associated with new technologies are some other 
factors that affect farmland consolidation 
edwards said a number of factors are working against the 
tendency to farm consolidation including 
selling off parcels of land for city growth can result in a 
larger number of small farms 
nonfarm incomes help ensure survival of smaller farm 
operations including parttime and hobby farms 
some farms that produce specialty commodities appear small by 
some measures but are proving profitable and durable 
larger farms sometimes reach a size beyond which they can grow 
no more and may even break up into smaller farms census 
information shows that large farms are just as likely to break 
into small ones as small farms are to blossom into large ones 
