<TEXT>
union pacific corp said thursday it 
will close the regional offices of its energy and mining subsidiary 
in denver and houston and consolidate those operations in fort 
worth by the end of the year 
the consolidation and reduced overhead from the recently 
announced sales of the companys wilmington calif refinery and 
its calnev pipe line co should help the union pacific resources 
co save at least 45 million a year said william l adams 
chairman and chief executive officer 
the consolidation at union pacifics corporate headquarters will 
add 400 jobs to the 550 that already exist in fort worth but the 
reorganization will eliminate about 400 jobs throughout the 
company he said 
it is clear that the expense of maintaining our regional 
offices cannot be justified in todays volatile and depressed oil 
pricing environment adams said thus we are streamlining to 
maintain our position as a lowcost finder and producer of oil and 
gas 
were going to do everything we can to cushion the blow for 
those affected including ample severance pay and outplacement 
services adams said while we will close offices in denver and 
houston we will still be active participants in the energy 
business in both areas 
union pacific resources will maintain production offices in rock 
springs wyo and wilmington and the firm will continue to operate 
its minerals group from denver adams said operations of the 
firms canadian subsidiary union pacific resources inc of 
calgary will be unchanged 
since the 1986 oil price collapse that sent prices from 24 to 
10 a barrel union pacific has been affected by the nationwide 
trend in which the domestic oil and gas industry lost some 400000 
jobs adams said 
in response to the 1986 collapse we have instituted various 
cost containment measures that including this reorganization will 
result in annual savings in excess of 267 million before tax 
adams said 
union pacific resources now has 375 people in its denver office 
and 325 in houston 
union pacific also announced three executive appointments as 
part of the consolidation on jan 1 robert s jackson now vice 
presidentfinance becomes executive vice president and chief 
financial officer dale w bossert vice president and regional 
managerdenver becomes vice president of production and george 
lindahl iii regional exploration managerhouston becomes vice 
presidentexploration 
