us labor secretary ann mclaughlin 
and one of her predecessors offered sharply contrasting opinions 
thursday on whether the united states has lost its competitive edge 
in world trade 
im not sure were behind mrs mclaughlin said at the third 
annual rhode island conference on labormanagement relations 
right now exports are up and the trade deficit is falling 
but ray marshall labor secretary during the carter 
administration said that while some economic measures of 
competitiveness may not indicate a decline the united states has 
fallen behind in productivity and real income levels 
marshall in a speech to more than 300 business and academic 
officials said the next president will have to define a clear set 
of goals before the country will again become competitive with 
other countries 
we have a passive trade policy they have an active trade 
policy he said the country with an active trade policy will 
win because they know where they want to get and how theyre going 
to get there 
mrs mclaughlin in an interview and an upbeat speech to the 
