<TEXT>
the fraud indictment of a florida citrus 
company is the first growing out of a 22month nationwide 
investigation of illegal citrus practices involving hundreds of 
millions of dollars federal officials said thursday 
it was the first indictment but the investigation is not 
limited to florida said brad knutter supervisor of the the 
tampa us customs fraud group which is coordinating the probe 
the lengthy probe dubbed operation orange squeeze is an 
unprecedented investigation by the us customs service of the 
citrus industry in florida and other citrusproducing states 
officals said 
a highland city citrus processor its ohio parent company and 
two of its former presidents were indicted tuesday accused of 
conspiring to bilk the federal government in a customs rebate scam 
allsun pure juice corp ohio pure foods inc of akron ohio 
and two former allsun executives robert w hurley 57 of lakeland 
and herman b cohen 67 of ormond beach were charged with 
mislabeling export products between 1983 and 1986 in order to 
collect 776458 in us customs rebates 
authorities charge the defendants attempted to cheat the 
government by labeling almost 2 million gallons of citrus pulpwash 
as frozen concentrated orange juice in 36 export shipments 
pulpwash is the residual citrus product left after the primary 
juice claim those rebates for 
exporting pulpwash an inferior citrus byproduct authorities say 
trying to pass the pulpwash off as concentrated orange juice was a 
fraud the indictment says 
the defendants have so far declined to comment on charges listed 
in the indictment 
custom laws allow companies 99 percent refund of import duties 
if products made from imported merchandise are later exported the 
rebate also is allowed if the export is produced from a domestic 
substitute of the same kind and quality as the dutypaid import 
officials say more charges are expected against other exporters 
pulpwash may be one of the more fraudulent activities but 
were not limiting the investigation to that knutter said 
in order to track exports he said investigators have to trace 
shipping records and trucking reports involving a number of 
companies 
this is just the start said customs agent steve bowman 
well be busy for a while 
bowman said investigators discovered a number of citrus 
concentrate exporters involved in the practice of mislabeling 
pulpwash as concentrate to get the rebates 
when asked if future cases involved as much as hundreds of 
millions of dollars bowman said overall that would be a 
conservative estimate 
customs officials said the agencys findings could hurt the 
credibility of floridas citrus industry 
operation orange squeeze has exposed a situation that could 
have a devastating effect on the florida citrus industry said 
customs agent bonni tischler in tampa following natural 
disasters like the freezes of recent years and the citrus canker 
infestations the last thing the florida orange growers and 
processors need is a company defrauding the government in order to 
make a few extra dollars 
only about 3 percent of the florida industry involves citrus 
concentrate exporting according to dr robert behr economic 
research director for the citrus department 
processors legitimately sell pulpwash to beverage companies who 
use it to produce diluted citrus drinks 
revenue in the industry totaled more than 3 billion last 
season he said of that amount about 100 million comes from 
concentrate exports according to behr 
</TEXT>
