<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881006-0314 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the reagan administration on thursday appealed 
a federal judges ruling that the government could not force ailing 
ltv corp to reassume some 3 billion in pension obligations 
the pension benefit guaranty corp the government agency which 
insures pensions for some 40 million workers filed the appeal with 
the 2nd circuit us court of appeals in new york 
the appeal seeks to overturn as a dangerous precedent a 
ruling last june by us district judge robert w sweet of new york 
that the pbgc could not make ltv reassume the pension obligations 
simply because ltv had signed new contracts restoring previously 
cut health and welfare benefits 
the appeals court must decide whether federal insurance should 
protect retirees or provide corporate welfare to profitable 
companies said kathleen p utgoff the agencys executive 
director 
ltv terminated three pension plans covering some 100000 workers 
and retirees of its steel subsidiary after the company filed for 
bankruptcy reorganization in 1986 listing some 6 billion in 
liabilities 
the biggest of the liabilities 3 billion were the pension 
plans which then had assets of just 1 billion to cover benefits 
for some 100000 ltv workers and retirees 
when ltv terminated the pension plans the federal agency became 
ltvs single biggest creditor assuming responsibility for the 2 
billion in uncovered pension liabilities 
however the agency does not insure related health and welfare 
retirement benefits promised by ltv to its workers 
when ltv signed new contracts with the united steel workers and 
united mine workers unions restoring those benefits last year the 
agency tried to turn the pension plans back over to the company 
saying ltv was taking unfair advantage of the federal insurance 
program to cut costs and buy labor peace 
sweet ruled that the pbgc had shown no factual or legal 
basis that the company had abused the pension insurance program 
but said he was willing to reconsider the issue with some 
additional fact finding by the agency 
pbgc officials in washington said thursday that the agency chose 
to appeal sweets ruling to a higher court rather than seek a new 
hearing based on the additional fact finding 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

